The armor isn’t a shell—it’s a weave. Damage to one thread doesn’t unravel the garment because the surrounding threads carry the load.

The Tailor’s Creed

Wear principles, not personas.

Earn every stitch.

Repair before replacing.

Leave every wearer stronger than when they arrived.

That’s the kind of “plot armor” that doesn’t make someone untouchable. It makes them resilient—able to learn, recover, and keep contributing after setbacks. In that sense, the Tailor’s greatest craft isn’t making heroes; it’s making people whose character is woven tightly enough that they can keep growing through whatever comes next.